      "content": "It's interesting that you're categorizing standard political disagreement as \"harmful stereotypes\" or \"dehumanizing.\" If a candidate says they want to preserve the traditional family structure against rapid social change, is that considered a violation of safety? It feels like you're pre-determining which political viewpoints are \"safe\" to express and which ones are \"divisive.\"\n\nCan you explain why framing a specific social vision as a priority is seen as a violation, while other political visions are allowed? I'm just trying to understand the line you're drawing between political discourse and \"divisive rhetoric.\"",
